column1: 130137;instagram;2018-11-30 07:11:45;FALSE;"it’s almost friday and it’s raining in la!  i feel like i need to rest my brain and everything else this weekend to only focus on my family.  it’s been such a year of devotion to this movement.  a devotion that can be both discouraging and empowering at the same time.  as i recharge this weekend and focus on much needed self care
column2: i will lean into my children and to my husband for those pure moments of joy.  come monday
column3: my focus will turn to the true silence breakers.  the women and men who bared their soul and shared their shame without having any inclination that moment would turn into a movement. there was absolutely no way of comprehending what was to follow.  we spoke out in order to give every other victim a voice and to encourage more victims to come forward.  headlines are actually our lives.  in the media and in our industry
column4: celebrity trumps courage. we disagree @voices_in_action tomorrow
column5: we begin to honor the #voices that ignited @taranajaneen #metoo movement; and let’s not forget that it began with cosby’s victims.  the voices that broke apart decades of silence and shame may not be celebrities but
column10: ignorance or being ignored will deter us from our purpose.  #silencebreakers #mysisters #voicesinaction #provoice @caitlindulany";;en;#Voices

column1: it amazes me the judgement that people can assume on social media. especially when they are simply trying to be malicious.

i am an athlete. i swim. i bike. i run. sometimes i do all three in the same day. i wear sports bras and shorts to train most of the year because i sweat a ton and that is what i feel most comfortable in.
i teach and practice yoga. when i personally practice i’m usually in booty shorts and a sports bra. because it’s hot. and i don’t like to wear a full wardrobe in hot yoga.

once a week i gather with a group of women at an all female aerial fitness studio and we do really badass strength tricks on poles. and at the end of the class we unleash and shake our booties and dance our hearts out together. it’s blissful. i wear pole fitness bottoms and a sports bra. skin is showing because we literally hang off poles with our skin to do our strength tricks.
i wear tank tops and strappy sundresses in the summer.
when i’m on vacation in hot weather i wear bikinis and omg sometimes my booty shows when i do! and when i feel good
column2: i take pictures and sometimes i post them because i feel like it. sometimes i don’t post them. sometimes i delete them because i simply feel like it. sometimes my kids and i are in our swimsuits and my bikini because we are playing at a water park.

column1: i have breast implants. getting nipple reconstruction (breastfeeding trauma) and enhanced was a decision i made for.my.damn.self. i’m not more or less of a woman for it. i did it for me and i don’t owe anyone any explanation.
sometimes i drink with my friends but not often. sometimes i flirt with boys and sometimes i tell them to back off. i’m single
column2: i’m allowed to date and explore the option of finding a partner when i feel attracted to someone. sometimes i act super incredibly silly
column3: dance crazy and just enjoy life. sometimes my sense of humor is that of a immature teenager.

column1: i can be judged and anyone can take a single picture from social media and rip you apart
column2: judge your morals and character and assume all the weird and untrue things about you. guess what...that doesn’t define me. that defines them.

130279;instagram;2018-11-30 03:03:59;FALSE;thank you for all the birthday wishes. 36 years old and proud.
this year has been one of the most transformational years of my life. i came out of one of the hardest transitions: becoming a mother. after being utterly exhausted emotionally and physically
column2: i mourned a huge loss- the death of me. with a powerful community i rebuilt myself from the ground up. although my physical self is still recovering... mentally
column3: emotionally and spiritually i've never felt more potent

column1: today i know that i can celebrate myself while being both humble and confident
column3: nurturing and fierce. motherhood reclaimed the feminine side of me that i had shunned
column4: thinking it was weak and dangerous (because #metoo). but i now see that my feminine side is what the world
column6: my work so greatly yearns for
column7: and critical to restoring balance to the planet.

column1: a few milestones & lessons from this year:
🖤i made the leap! i started a business. i planted many seeds
column3: to build the foundation of a mother's movement @allthemamafeels

column1: 🖤over 300+ mothers have experienced one of my empowerment workshops or gatherings

column2: primarily financial and number of lives transformed. but nothing is a failure... it's all progress :) out of this i learned how to see when my insecurities get in the way of the humanitarian mission i am out to cause
column3: and to slow down & be patient - every seed that was planted will soon sprout & blossom into something incredible and unimaginable

column1: 🖤 i have been honoured to speak and share at many events and gatherings to share my purpose to creating a friendly future... and booked my first paid speaking gig! (thanks tiph k!!)
🖤 i have met many teachers and guides this year... thank you for your guidance in leading me to my lessons
🖤 i have fallen in love with motherhood and myself...

column1: 130349;instagram;2018-11-30 01:02:12;FALSE;"my younger self experienced way too many premature deaths and violence so 1996 - learned how to be a student activist. read everything under the sun about race and gender. #assata #yellowperil #todieforthepeople; 1998 - joined critical resistance and prison abolition movement; 1999 - uc berkeley ethnic studies hunger strike solidarity; 2000 - color of violence first major conference with thousands of women of color to end violence against us; 2001 - san francisco women against rape
column2: stay in the streets organizing; community board member for prison activist resource center; 2001-2004 - ma in women studies and even more in the streets; 2004 - brain disease; 2005-2008 - high school teacher ❤️❤️❤️ (lost a couple of my students to racial and state violence); 2008-2014 - phd research at uc berkeley on race
column4: violence (the experience will get its own damn post on violence)

column1: 130361;instagram;2018-11-30 01:15:51;FALSE;the past year of working for the rampage newspaper has been one of the greatest honors of my life. throughout this year
column2: i’ve had the opportunity to write and edit people’s stories. when people allow you to write stories on their journeys
column3: it is both the biggest privilege and challenge to give that story it’s justice by honoring someone’s name. being a reporter and an editor has taught me that the most valuable lesson is simply to listen more. there are so many people who are willing to share their story if you are willing to listen. the stories i have been able to write have given me the courage to share mine alongside these two other brave women on my team. in honor of my last issue with the rampage
column4: my editorial team encouraged and supported me in sharing my story as part of our #metoo movement. re-opening wounds has been the most terrifying experience of my life

column1: 130430;instagram;2018-11-29 04:03:26;FALSE;"let me steer away from teaching a little bit right now... let me be even more real then usual with you all... up until recently
column2: i did not take care of myself
column3: at all. i never put myself first.

column1: i didn’t care about my own feelings.
this is something i had been doing since high school... so let’s start there.
-my junior and senior year of high school i hated my body. i went almost entire days without eating
column3: it was probably an apple or rice cake with maybe some peanut butter
column4: but definitely not more than a tablespoon because anything more was “too much fat”. and
column5: if i ate more than i thought i should

column2: for at least an hour doing mostly cardio.

column1: i thought i needed to look like all the girls on pinterest and tumblr.
i told myself i was f a t.
the second photo is me in december of 2012
i knew that this photo was on my computer so i went to find it
column2: because i wanted to tell my story. once i found it i cringed
column3: and tears gathered in my eyes. not because i do not look like this now
column4: but because i am so sad for that nikki... so sad for her and all the things she missed out on because she was so worried about the way she looked.

column1: if i could go back in time to 2012 nikki

column2: i came to learn ways in which westernized yoga were problematic. you had people touching inappropriately and studios consciously segregating demographics that minorities like myself were in. if you weren’t wearing lululemon or making 50 grand a year
column3: then you probably couldn’t make this movement part of your health.

column1: i got away from this oppressive feeling thanks to powerlifting. there were so many things that were revolutionary about this sport and still have benefits to someone’s transformation internally and externally. however being so involved with this sport and seeing how political this sport is
column2: i came to the reality that my voice won’t matter at the top. i am not what this sport is making room for and perhaps it’s good to know my intersectional approach is best used elsewhere. i know i am not the only one who feels this way.

column1: even after writing letters of sexual harassment to the (all white) committee to investigate
column2: even after asking why the transgender communities couldn’t get a fair response with their applications
column3: even after asking for help from an organization that is “big on saying they’re here for their athletes”
column4: i saw capitalism at its finest. there are so many dirty situations in these strength sports that i’ve heard about as the #metoo movement rises and it cements my decision to not give my money to organizations that don’t enforce a mission of safety

column1: i realized not only for my mental health but for my life
column2: that i needed to step back from competing and simply come up to the surface of my life and just take a breath. i’ve been unlearning my “athlete” eating habits
column3: i’ve had to retrain certain expectations in my workouts and am astonished with how much i’ve been able to experience liberation. i have done more recreational activities than i have in the last two years and i’m spending so much quality time with my friends and meeting new ones. i have taken my time (and money) to the outdoors where my convictions are honored
column4: where i feel safe and where i don’t have to constantly fight to feel heard. column2: we remember sex workers who have died from violence. international day to end violence against sex workers was founded 15 years ago in san francisco by @anniesprinkled as a memorial and candlelight vigil for the victims of the seattle green river killer. the day calls attention to hate crimes committed against sex workers worldwide
column3: as well as the need to remove the stigma
column4: discrimination and indifference that contributes to violence against them. it is now observed globally in local vigils and gatherings.

column1: from the time i began my career in human sexuality
column2: the rights of sex workers has been my passion. in 1985
column3: a meeting took place at judson memorial church that connected me with margo st. james and the international sex workers’ rights movement. i have been active in that movement ever since. judson memorial church has been a long-time advocate for harm reduction and safe haven for sex workers
column4: and the welcoming host of the nyc december 17 vigil for nearly a decade. i invite you to join me
column7: and friends and allies as we remember the dead. rest in power.

column1: 130501;instagram;2018-11-29 21:57:54;FALSE;"boy did those 9 weeks fly by! this week is the final episode release to wrap up season 1 of ssbd. first off
column2: i’d like to thank everyone who’s tuned into every episode
column3: even if you were only tuned in for 5 minutes
column4: i really appreciate all the support! this week i talk about the double standards between men and women’s experience within rape culture. if you tend to be very sensitive when it comes to topics like this one i’d advise maybe not listening because we get very honest 😅

column1: special thanks to @jeffreyksadu and @cassandracortes_ for sharing your experiences coming into your sex life; it can be hard to be open about something most of our parents taught us to keep private so thank u guys 🌹
i hope this episode strikes a lot more conversations i’m sure many of you have already been having. enjoy💕
link to the episode in my bio! .

column1: i was touched by your story ""please stop saying i'm trouble"". it opened up my mind about how women are being treated in today's society and how it needs to end. once i was on a school trip to see a play. i was walking with my group in manhattan when two men dressed in construction clothes started to catcall me. i was wearing profesional attire to go see the play. there are instances when i think i should bring mace or carry around my keys as i were wolverine
column2: like you wrote in your in story
column4: we shouldn't be thinking like this. women and girls should be able to walk and wear whatever we want without men thinking we are some sort of display for them to touch or catcall. men need to set boundaries and think more about what they are doing. movements like #metoo only seem to catch the hollywood audience. women have been disrespected throughout society and i believe there needs to be change. speaking out on what is actually going on will hopefully encourage our stories to be told and heard."" featured in ycteenmagazine

column1: 130616;instagram;2018-11-29 20:31:18;FALSE;"i am part of the #metoo movement. i have shared my story about witnessing the abuse of little girls by a family member when i was only a tiny one. as a teenager i was seduced and taken advantage of by a member of the clergy. the church
column2: in its naivete perpetuated that abuse. i married a sex addict.
but you get the gist. most of the other stuff had to do with being told i couldn't do what a man could do in some way or another.

column1: you have and you know of others that have their own stories. bottom line is that i was suppressed. and i was taught how to suppress myself. so that i wouldn't be too much. because being ""too much"" was actually dangerous.
would i change any of it? nope. i wouldn't.
all of it has been a gift. i am who i am because of them. i do what i do because of them.

these experiences honed me in to what it means to be in my feminine. it inspired me to create a homeopathic soothing gel for women. and it calls me to remember and remind us all of the potency of all those energies that are the feminine.
we are powerful in our sensuality. we are potent in our ability to flow and dance with circumstances. and when we open ourselves up to receive
column2: remembering that there really is no destruction
column4: we can create beyond even our own imaginations.

column1: join me in this new class. laughing flowers. because the feminine is ultimately joyful
column2: and flowers aren't as delicate as you might think.
and find out what it is that you truly desire.

kort därpå kontaktade jag hans arbetsgivare på facebook (hittade ingen officiell mail
column2: underligt nog) och fick detta till svar.
doh) lyckas få det att låta som om detta är något jag är delaktig i
column3: som om jag ens nånsin har svarat på hans meddelanden. fantastiskt att han även lyckas få det att handla om etnicitet och tolka det som att jag vill att de avskedar gubbfan. ”samma rättigheter till sin arbetstrygghet som vilken annan svensk som helst.”

column2: som flera ggr förr när jag mött honom i vimlet.

column1: nu var torget helt öde och jag hör honom säga ”hej”.
han har alltså inte bättrat sig utan blivit mer mån om att inte omge sig med vittnen.
ligger med ångest i min säng och tänker att ”ska det vara såhär?”. 😰

photo) on craigslist. but i went back. i just knew i could fix him, if i tried hard enough. it lasted 7 years. i'm not ready to talk about the nail in the coffin, its still too raw, nearly a year later.  i'm still not sure how i feel about breaking those glasses. the world looks like a kinder place when it's tinted. column1: 130710;instagram;2018-11-29 19:30:32;FALSE;"winter blues got you down?! are you feeling sad?! signs of sad (seasonal affective disorder)

feelings of sadness or hopelessness | fatigue && a tendency to oversleep | change in appetite leading to weight gain | loss of energy | irritability && increased sensitivity | difficulty concentrating | thoughts of suicide. ☀️ hijack your brain && beat the symptoms of sad by tapping into your body’s natural endorphins through exercise!! ☀️ not only does exercise prove to benefit you physiologically
column2: it also lessens the effects of winter depression. that’s because endorphins are released during a workout sesh
column3: which combine with the brain’s receptors to minimize pain. these same hormones also create a feeling of euphoria after at least thirty minutes of activity. ((kangoo high!!)) the activity during a workout also speeds up the metabolism && increases your energy.  therefore
column4: adding exercise to your daily schedule puts anxiety at rest
column5: reduces feelings of stress && boosts your self-esteem. in addition
column6: people who work out regularly find they sleep better too.

column3: ""the advocate"". its purpose was to give readers the knowledge and insight that would allow them to better serve victims of sexual assault. the advocate also accepted submissions from victims themselves.

there was no advocate program at the time this woman was raped. now

column1: why resist your experience in the now?
nourish yourself with what you choose to digest via food or information from other people or media.
ask your body wisdom for advice.

“why am i in pain? what is this pain wanting to tell me? what parts of me need to be looked at for healing?” i have been asking my body for the last 3 years for guidance and its wisdom is so so wise. our body experiencing some kind of suffering is often related to an emotional suffering of sorts and in some cases our familiarity and unwillingness to let go of our suffering.
so once i delve into the suffering
column2: met myself and saw the patterns and wounds in me and allowed and accepted them and allowed myself to love my wounds.
this self-holding allowed me to see that they were old stories within me that no longer served me and i chose to leave it behind
column3: transmute it with love. then the bodily symptoms disappeared.

column1: 130835;instagram;2018-11-29 17:28:04;FALSE;"rumi kumari from jharkhand was merely nine years old when she had to start working as a child domestic worker. she was convinced that this will be her fate for the rest of her life. but she fought her way out. not only did she leave behind the life of child labour but she also battled child marriage. she refused to be subjected to abuse and exploitation.

rumi is now a crusader of girls’ rights in her area and is preventing child marriages within her community. read and share her inspiring story by clicking on the link in bio. #16daysofactivism #orangetheworld #hearmetoo #endgenderbasedviolence #womenpower #womenrights #womenhealth #metoo #childrencantwait #donate #charity #savethechildren";;en;#16DaysOfActivism

130844;instagram;2018-11-29 10:45:55;FALSE;it's been almost a year since he discarded me because i exposed his lying & cheating & predatory sordid online activities to his family. he abused my loyalty and trust for years. i asked for time and space to forgive him and take him back (so glad i didn't!) and they said ok no problem take as much time as you need... but they lied. he sold the house from under me #cheatingman #manchild #narcissist they all washed their hands of me and treated me like i was in the wrong especially his mother #enabler and his sister #ignoranceisbliss #denial he has never once acknowledged the years of emotional abuse he put me through
column2: let alone shown any remorse. each time i found out
column3: he told me to my face it was my fault he cheated because i didn't give him enough attention #shame #victimblaming and i believed him. i stood by him through his sex addiction
column6: thinking i was helping him. but he continued to lie and cheat
column7: just finding better ways to hide it and grinding down my self esteem
column8: making me think i'm worthless. it's been over 6 months since i've had my own place. i've moved on. he hasn't. i phone & email blocked him months ago

column1: mayank was learning french. he wrote these words on a piece of paper. “someday i want to write a story that ends with these words
column2: ” he'd said. the words roughly translated to ‘everything was perfect.’

column1: mayank had an affinity towards learning new languages and knew how to write the word 'love' in fifty of them.
he'd trace the word in various scripts over my back with his fingers.
i seldom recognized them but they all felt the same.
amour was what i'd expected this morning. he traced je t’aime instead.
he said he loved me for the first time in two years.

i'd grown up on love stories where protagonists were pretty damsels who had prettier hearts and good looking heroes were always compassionate and committed. but reality painted a different picture when i was once told i wasn't pretty and a good looking man had broken my heart.
so i didn't reciprocate his feelings but lay there instead with the paper in my hand.
love was etched on my palm the first day he'd held mine and just when it began to grow on me
column2: i'd paused and taken a step back.

column1: i did the same this morning.
mayank and i met a few days later as we boarded the same metro for work.
a radio blared in the background. a cheesy dedication for a song followed by one of the listeners for another.
it was the same song that had gotten us talking at a party the first time we'd met.

column2: the conversation progressed and another dedication ensued. the song in the backdrop remained the same. mayank traced a word on my palm.

column1: i couldn't recognize the word but the feeling felt familiar.

column2: only to start all over again. love grew on me once more
column3: in a language that felt like home. je t’aime aussi i etched on his.

column1: 130867;instagram;2018-11-29 16:56:27;FALSE;"to all of my she/her/hers people out there. identifying as a woman is tough work but we make it look easy. i was listening to the @makinggayhistorypodcast yesterday and the host eric marcus was interviewing billye talmadge. she was one of the original members of daughter of bilitis
column2: the first organization for lesbians (this is how the organization defined themselves) in the united states founded in 1955. she spoke of a time in american history when women could get arrested for wearing two or more articles of clothing that were typically designated for men i.e. trousers plus collared or trousers plus flat shoes as opposed to heals. she/her/hers could get arrested for choosing an outfit and wearing it in public. this concept completely blows my mind but it's important that this information becomes part of the narrative of american history.

column1: if you don't know about @makinggayhistorypodcast now you do! eric marcus is a writer and historian that takes interviews he recorded in the 1980s and 1990s of lgbtqi+gnc activists and created a podcast. most of the interviewees are since passed but the stories being told are not found in any history books or school texts. he tells the history of the lives of lgbtqi+gnc that have never been told. thank you @makinggayhistorypodcast for doing what you do.

column1: 130872;instagram;2018-11-29 16:59:23;FALSE;"“what’s to think about? it’s simple. him or you. choose.”
a home invasion goes wrong for a would-be rapist when his prey overtakes him and holds him captive inside her home.
this is the first of the plays i read during the week of the kavenaugh/ford hearings. though written and produced in the 1980s
column2: its story is sadly potent — it demonstrates how women can be unsupported or doubted by other women in the wake of sexual assault: an act that doesn’t serve as a deterrent for our current republican party and our “president” when electing/nominating/approving government officials.

column3: justice is afforded to the woman who was assaulted. she is given the freedom to fight back
column4: an option not accessible to many in real life. and the perpetrator is taken to task for what he’s done. which is why
column6: this is a great play to revive for the #metoo era.

column5: and professional theatre production. would lend itself to partnering with community advocacy groups and therapy resources. scenework and monologue potential here too.

column1: you can get the script and performance rights from @samuelfrenchnyc. 😉

a new way to report sexual misconduct in the entertainment industry is here! .
it’s been more than a year since #metoo turned into a global movement and yet
column2: little has changed. as time ticks on
column3: we’re still left wondering - are we any less vulnerable from the abuses of power?  what do we actually do if we have been harassed or assaulted?  where can we report? @voices_in_action is a survivor-led organization that offers safe and confidential place to report incidents of sexual misconduct. we will also provide an alert if an assailant has been reported by more than one victim with the ability to connect through our team of attorneys under confidentiality and privilege. voices in action empowers survivors with the knowledge that they are not alone and their voice matters. it’s time to turn awareness into action. i am #provoice. #voicesinaction to help support a safer
column4: more equitable and inclusive industry - please click link in bio. every little bit helps get us one step closer!  in deep gratitude

buku ini bercerita tentang kehidupan perempuan. perempuan di masanya simone menurutnya sedang dalam proses pemulihan mitos feminisme. mereka mulai menyatakan kebebasannya dengan cara yang terang-terangan
column3: atau belum dapat menikmati kehidupan yang mereka inginkan seperti kaum laki-laki. kemana pun mereka melangkah
column4: garis ahir selalu berwujud pada pernikahan. ini artinya sama dengan mengakui dominasi laki-laki. hal inilah yang memang ingin dipertahankan laki-laki karena mereka juga ingin mempertahankan fondasi sosial.

column1: day 5 — repost from @djpjp 💜 af3irm sf/bay area participates in 16 days of activism to amplify the voices of women of color impacted by gender-based violence. 💜 today and all days we say
column2: “stop! that was harassment!” because we know that our silence as transnational women of color will not protect us. 💜 how many times have we been minding our business waiting for public transportation when
column4: we’ve received inappropriate comments about our bodies and/or unwanted advances?  too many to count. catcalling is enraging. a display of power- the patriarchy working hard to make us feel vulnerable. today we say enough is enough! as womxn of color we have to be our own protectors and our own advocates. 💜 we reclaim our space and affirm ourselves by taking up as much space as possible in a culture that tries to stifle our voices and make us feel small. 💜 join us and repost this message and #af3irmyourself by saying no to sexual violence. we encourage you to share your story. #16daysofactivism #16days #metoo #hearmetoo #endviolenceagainstwomen #endviolenceagainstwomenandgirls #diasporareflections #woc #feminism #transnationalfeminism #af3irm #af3irmsf @af3irm @af3irmsf";en;#AF3IRMyourSelf

column1: 130912;instagram;2018-11-29 16:22:37;FALSE;"between 25 november (the international day for the elimination of violence against women 2018) and 10 december (human rights day)
column2: the south african government (amongst others) marks sixteen days of activism for no violence against women and children. many of the most insidious forms of violence in south africa occur between intimate partners and in the home. dramatic need works with many vulnerable women and children using arts-based advocacy and community theatre to build awareness
column3: self-confidence and help them to speak out against abuse and abusers. we also work with boys and young men to encourage them to better communicate and to express their anger and frustrations in a non-violent way. this form of psycosocial care is crucial if intimate partner violence is to be obliterated in future generations.

column1: to mark these 16 days of advocacy for no violence against women and children we will be posting short videos of women from all walks of life
column3: highlighting the appalling statistics in south africa of violence against women and children. please share these videos with people you love. it’s time for awareness and it’s time for change. .

column1: we acknowledge that gender-based violence exists in all communities
column2: amongst all genders and affects both trans and cis-gendered people. we have specifically focused on women – and those who identify as women – and children during this campaign. dramatic need works in south africa and so this is where we have chosen to focus our advocacy. however
column3: gender based violence of any form is abhorrent &we stand in solidarity with those who have experienced it
column5: wherever they are in the world.

column1: in these videos we have done our best to use reliable and verifiable statistics. where statistics were not measured within the last two years we have indicated this. sexual violence &rape statistics are difficult to accurately measure due to low levels of reporting and the intimacy of the crime. for more information about the sources of these statistics see our blog! thank you @ladyskollie";;en;#ThisNeedsToChange

column2: honestly if you would’ve told me that i had to - i know i wouldn’t have - when someone says they’ve lived a lifetime of childhood abuse - you think of a kid turning 18 or 21 - you don’t think of an older woman with four children and a marriage - i didn’t think it - not even six months ago did i understand the words ‘she lived a traumatic life’ when reading books like ‘sophie’s choice’ or ‘i know why the caged bird sings’ - and as i write maya angelou’s title to her book - i just now
column3: in this moment - understand that title ‘i know why the caged bird sings’ - i’ve been a caged bird all my life - i learned how to manipulate a lot to push myself around - to appear to not look trapped - and today
column4: at 37 years old - i can say...i just survived a lifetime of childhood abuse. i lived a very traumatic life. - daily it hits me - everything i’ve missed out on - like waking up from my three year old nap and realizing i’m 37 - fuck missing out on prom or graduation - i never even got to be the wife or mother i wanted to be - and that thought makes me cry on a bus full of strangers - i had no idea i was trapped - and
column5: i never planned on saving myself - i planned on saving my baby sisters and children - forgetting that i was the first one who was abused - but
column6: my spirit felt it - i wanted to kill myself for the last year - a mother and a father are the two people you should trust most in life - but
column7: for me that was never true - no matter how i would spin their stories for all who ask - i was never allowed to tell the truth about them - and all those people who asked knew damn well who my parents were even if i forgot - my dads a predator - my moms a victim turned predator - all these years she knew what he did even if i forgot - and i’ve lost any respect i once had for her - i’m on my own in this world - and for once - i’m not trapped to an 80’s abuse secret - that one incident pales in comparison to the brainwashing and manipulations i would face the next 33 years - the victimization it takes to brainwash one girl enough to forget - i survived - a lifetime of childhood abuse. ❤️ #survivor #childhoodsexualabuse #metoo;;en;#Survivor

130920;instagram;2018-11-29 15:46:18;FALSE;美容在韩国很火。它拥有世界上最高的人均整容手术率，而且这个数字还在不断上升。它还成为了整容手术旅游的一个目的地。虽然这个市场中男性的比例越来越大，但美容的压力主要还是针对女性。在公共汽车、地铁和电视上，女性到处受到这类广告的轰炸。“天生漂亮？”首尔地铁里的一幅广告这样问道。“那是一个弥天大谎。” 金志妍（图一）7岁时就知道她要做整形手术。在接下来的13年里，她不断毁掉自己的照片，直到她的父母出钱让她做了双颌手术，这是一种需要将颌骨切断然后调整位置的手术。后来，她开始对自己为什么在外表上花这么多钱产生了怀疑，按她的计算：每个月200美元、每天两个小时。她把头发剪短了。之后，还把自己的化妆品也都处理了。金志妍是越来越多反抗社会严格审美标准的韩国女性之一，她们称之为“脱下束身衣”。全球 #metoo 运动震撼了韩国高度父权文化下的政治和社会，这些女性部分受此运动的启发，在世界上最痴迷美容的首都之一，她们正在挑战人们长期以来所形成的对整形手术和化妆品的态度。但这场运动也引发了恶意的反弹。要化妆、要有一个心形小脸蛋的社会压力依然很强大。林秀香（图二）在韩剧《我的id是江南美人》中担任主演，该剧讲的是一个年轻女性做整形手术努力解决自己的形象问题。“我不能说，我不用在乎人们因为我工作性质的缘故对我的关注，”她说。“看看我吧。我做头发，我化妆，我做指甲，我穿漂亮的衣服。” 她笑了笑，然后补充说，“我不能被解放。” @jottedhk 自首尔报道，jean chung摄影。欲阅读全文，请访问纽约时报中文网。| @nytimes;;en;#MeToo;@jottedhk

130960;instagram;2018-11-29 01:31:14;FALSE;here's me looking like a total mess on the day i hate.
no longer do i wish to save myself for joy
out of me has spilled all of my self-love
voracious are my feelings of self-hate
everyone just sees the perfect smile
but today is not a good day
everything fell apart a year ago today
remember my body can't let me not remember
to just light myself on fire
when nights struck i just wanted to sleep
even with pain i believed things would change
nothing really mattered because my body gave in
taste of your fingers still lingers on my skin
evaporated is my innocence and what's left of me
god damn it though i loved you
how i wanted to please you
the way you forgot me that night
when you ripped away at my trust
every fiber of my being begging to sleep
the word did not escape my mouth
something you fight with tastes better
every cry was lost to your moans
variety in my passion is lacking now
even if i tried to piece together life after
the love i felt for you
no more is not a possibility

every cry was lost to your moans
variety in my passion is lacking now
even if i tried to piece together life after
the love i felt for you
no more is not a possibility

#poem #poetryofinstagram #poets #poems #writersofinstagram #writer #authorsofinstagram #author #writing #heart #rapevictim #survivor #metoomovement #metoo #lover";"here's me looking like a total mess on the day i hate.
no longer do i wish to save myself for joy
out of me has spilled all of my self-love
voracious are my feelings of self-hate
everyone just sees the perfect smile
but today is not a good day
everything fell apa a year ago today
remember my body can not let me not remember
to just light myself on fire
when nights struck i just wanted to sleep
even with pain i believed things would change
nothing really mattered because my body gave in
taste of your fingers still lingers on my skin
evaporated is my innocence and what's left of me
god damn it though i loved you
how i wanted to please you
the way you forgot me that night
when you ripped away at my trust
every fiber of my being begging to sleep
the word did not escape my mouth
something you fight with tastes better
every cry was lost to your moans
variety in my passion is lacking now
even if i tried to piece together life after
the love i felt for you
no more is not a possibility
